+Findings:
+- [high] OpenClaw stop verification checks the wrong systemd user and treats errors as inactive (runtime/deploy/cutover.sh:355-363)
+  T+00 verifies OpenClaw with `systemctl --user` through the root SSH session, while rollback later manages the same unit via `su - ilsantino -c 'systemctl --user ...'`, indicating it is an `ilsantino` user unit. If root has no user bus, or the check otherwise fails, the `|| echo inactive` path makes the script accept the state as inactive. A failed archive/stop can therefore proceed into token rotation and v2 startup while OpenClaw is still running, creating duplicate gateway/bot processing during cutover.
+  Recommendation: Verify the OpenClaw unit through the same `ilsantino` user context used by rollback, and fail closed on systemctl/query errors instead of mapping them to `inactive`.
+- [high] Rollback can leave the failed v2 daemon enabled (runtime/deploy/rollback.sh:169-177)
+  Rollback runs `systemctl stop ... && systemctl disable ... || true`, then only checks whether the daemon is currently inactive. If `disable` fails, or if `stop` fails before `disable` is attempted, the script can still report success as long as the service is inactive at that moment. That leaves the failed v2 daemon enabled and able to restart on reboot or later systemd activity after OpenClaw has been restored, causing a split-brain recovery state.
+  Recommendation: Run stop and disable as separate operations, do not ignore disable failures, and assert `systemctl is-enabled iago-os-v2-daemon.service` is disabled or not-found before continuing.
+- [medium] Lock release can delete another run's lock marker (runtime/deploy/cutover.sh:231-234)
+  The remote flock is released when the SSH command exits, so ongoing exclusion relies on the persisted `.pid` marker. `release_remote_lock` deletes that marker unconditionally. If an operator breaks a stale lock while the old process is still alive, or another run acquires the marker before the old process exits, the old process's EXIT trap can remove the new run's marker. That opens the door for a third concurrent cutover/rollback despite the intended global lock.
+  Recommendation: Release the marker only if its contents still equal this process's `LOCK_MARKER`, ideally under the same remote flock; apply the same owner-checked cleanup to `rollback.sh`.
+
+Next steps:
+- Fix the state checks and lock ownership semantics before running this in production.
+- Add harness cases for OpenClaw query failure, disable failure, and owner-mismatched lock cleanup.
